A shell is the command interpreter that sits between you and your operating system's kernel. 
It's the bridge that translates your commands into actions the OS can execute.


The Shell Command Execution Cycle
┌──────────────┐
│   DISPLAY    │
│   PROMPT ($) │
└──────┬───────┘
       │
       ▼
┌──────────────┐
│  READ INPUT  │ (user types: ls -la)
└──────┬───────┘
       │
       ▼
┌──────────────┐
│    PARSE     │ (tokenize into: ls, -la)
└──────┬───────┘
       │
       ▼
┌──────────────┐
│   LOOKUP     │ (is it built-in or external?)
└──────┬───────┘
       │
       ▼
┌──────────────┐
│   EXECUTE    │ (run the command)
└──────┬───────┘
       │
       ▼
┌──────────────┐
│   DISPLAY    │ (show output)
└──────────────┘
Ex1: echo "Hello World"
Prompt: Shell displays $
User types: echo "Hello World"
Parser: Breaks into tokens: echo, "Hello World"
Lookup: Finds echo is a built-in command
Execute: Runs echo directly in the shell
Output: Displays Hello World

Ex2: ls -la /tmp
Prompt: Shell displays $
User types: ls -la /tmp
Parser: Breaks into: ls, -la, /tmp
Lookup: Finds ls is external program (searches PATH)
Execute:
Creates new process
Loads /bin/ls into memory
Passes arguments: -la /tmp
Output: Lists files/directories


Command-Line Shells (CLI)

| Shell | Origin | Features | Usage |
|-------|--------|----------|-------|
| sh (Bourne Shell) | 1979 | Basic, POSIX standard | System scripts, portability |
| bash (Bourne Again Shell) | 1989 | Extended sh, most popular | Default on Linux/macOS |
| csh (C Shell) | 1978 | C-like syntax | Some BSD systems |
| zsh (Z Shell) | 1990 | bash + csh + improvements | macOS Catalina default, power users |
| ksh (Korn Shell) | 1983 | Between sh and csh | Some Unix systems |
| fish (Friendly Interactive Shell) | 2005 | User-friendly, modern | Interactive use |
| PowerShell | 2006 | Object-oriented, Windows-focused | Windows systems |


